239, 240. ‘Since the mind does not allow that any of these substances can produce the motions that cause sensation, far less the thoughts which it ponders in itself’: i. e. warmth, wind, and air cannot be sup· posed to produce sensation, and much less to produce thought.

The expression is peculiar and seems to be ironical: the mind is represented as debating its own composition, much as the atoms (ii 978) are imagined as discussing theirs.
